==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang}} {{term|gat|gāt|lang=ang}} < {{proto|Germanic|gaitaz|lang=en}} < {{proto|Indo-European|gʰaid-|lang=en}}.  Cognate with Old High German {{term|geiz|lang=goh}} (German {{term|Geiß|lang=de}}), Old Norse {{term|geit|lang=non}} (Danish {{term|ged|lang=da}}, Swedish {{term|get|lang=sv}}), Gothic {{term|𐌲𐌰𐌹𐍄𐍃|tr=gaits|sc=Goth}}; and with Latin {{term|haedus||kid}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/gəʊt/}}
* {{audio|en-us-goat.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|əʊt}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun}}

# Any of various [[ruminant]] mammals, of the [[genus]] ''[[Capra]]'', related to the [[sheep]].  A group of goats is referred to as a {{term|tribe}} or a {{term|herd}}.
# {{slang}} A [[lecherous]] [[man]].
# {{informal}} A [[scapegoat]]
#* '''2008''', "Tigers already miss Jones", in ''Royal Oak Daily Tribune'' (Michigan), Aug 6, 2008
#*: Fernando Rodney, the '''goat''' in Sunday's 10th inning loss to Tampa Bay, threw three nearly perfect innings in relief on Tuesday after being demoted from the closer role.

